# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blossom-edmonds-contraction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] In graph theory, the **blossom algorithm** is an algorithm for constructing maximum matchings on graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The algorithm was developed by Jack Edmonds in 1961, and published in 1965.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Given a general graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), the algorithm finds a matching M such that each vertex in V is incident with at most one edge in M and |*M*| is maximized.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The matching is constructed by iteratively improving an initial empty matching along augmenting paths in the graph.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Unlike bipartite matching, the key new idea is that an odd-length cycle in the graph (blossom) is contracted to a single vertex, with the search continuing iteratively in the contracted graph.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The algorithm runs in time *O*(|*E*||*V*|2), where |*E*| is the number of edges of the graph and |*V*| is its number of vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] A better running time of $O(|E|{\sqrt {|V|}})$ for the same task can be achieved with the more complicated algorithm of Micali and Vazirani.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] A major reason that the blossom algorithm is important is that it gave the first proof that a maximum-size matching could be found using a polynomial amount of computation time.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Another reason is that it led to a linear programming polyhedral description of the matching polytope, yielding an algorithm for min-*weight* matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Given *G* = (*V*, *E*) and a matching M of G, a vertex v is **exposed** if no edge of M is incident with v.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] A path in G is an **alternating path**, if its edges are alternately not in M and in M (or in M and not in M).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] An **augmenting path** P is an alternating path that starts and ends at two distinct exposed vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Note that the number of unmatched edges in an augmenting path is greater by one than the number of matched edges, and hence the total number of edges in an augmenting path is odd.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] By Berge's lemma, matching M is maximum if and only if there is no M-augmenting path in G.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Hence, either a matching is maximum, or it can be augmented.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Thus, starting from an initial matching, we can compute a maximum matching by augmenting the current matching with augmenting paths as long as we can find them, and return whenever no augmenting paths are left.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] We still have to describe how augmenting paths can be found efficiently.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The subroutine to find them uses blossoms and contractions.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Given *G* = (*V*, *E*) and a matching M of G, a *blossom* B is a cycle in G consisting of 2*k* + 1 edges of which exactly k belong to M, and where one of the vertices v of the cycle (the *base*) is such that there exists an alternating path of even length (the *stem*) from v to an exposed vertex w.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Define the **contracted graph** G' as the graph obtained from G by contracting every edge of B, and define the **contracted matching** M' as the matching of G' corresponding to M.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Thus blossoms can be contracted and search performed in the contracted graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] This reduction is at the heart of Edmonds' algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The search for an augmenting path uses an auxiliary data structure consisting of a forest F whose individual trees correspond to specific portions of the graph G.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] In fact, the forest F is the same that would be used to find maximum matchings in bipartite graphs (without need for shrinking blossoms).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] In each iteration the algorithm either (1) finds an augmenting path, (2) finds a blossom and recurses onto the corresponding contracted graph, or (3) concludes there are no augmenting paths.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The auxiliary structure is built by an incremental procedure discussed next.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The construction procedure considers vertices v and edges e in G and incrementally updates F as appropriate.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] If v is in a tree T of the forest, we let *`root(v)`* denote the root of T.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] If both u and v are in the same tree T in F, we let *`distance(u,v)`* denote the length of the unique path from u to v in T.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The following four figures illustrate the execution of the algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Dashed lines indicate edges that are currently not present in the forest.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] First, the algorithm processes an out-of-forest edge that causes the expansion of the current forest (lines B10 – B12).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Next, it detects a blossom and contracts the graph (lines B20 – B21).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Finally, it locates an augmenting path P′ in the contracted graph (line B22) and lifts it to the original graph (line B23).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Note that the ability of the algorithm to contract blossoms is crucial here; the algorithm cannot find P in the original graph directly because only out-of-forest edges between vertices at even distances from the roots are considered on line B17 of the algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The forest F constructed by the `find_augmenting_path()` function is an alternating forest.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Each iteration of the loop starting at line B09 either adds to a tree T in F (line B10) or finds an augmenting path (line B17) or finds a blossom (line B20).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] It is easy to see that the running time is $O(|E||V|^{2})$ .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The Blossom algorithm is difficult to parallelize for several reasons.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] First, blossom contraction and lifting recursively change the graph structure, creating sequential dependencies between different stages of the search.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Second, a standard search iteration usually finds only one augmenting path, increasing the matching size by one at a time and requiring many iterations on large graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Third, the algorithm maintains dynamic structures, including alternating trees and contracted graphs, that are repeatedly updated during execution.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] In a parallel implementation, these updates may require synchronization and can introduce data races.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] These factors have made efficient parallel implementations of the Blossom algorithm highly challenging.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] X-Blossom provides an effective parallel solution for computing maximum matchings in general graphs and directly addresses these challenges.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] It first introduces a new recursion-free Blossom algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] In the traditional algorithm, a blossom is contracted during the search and later lifted when an augmenting path is found.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] By contrast, the recursion-free algorithm eliminates this contraction-and-lifting process.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The key observation is that, when constructing an augmenting path, preserving the full recursive contraction history is unnecessary.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The essential information is the appropriate even-length path through the blossom structure.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Thus, instead of contracting a blossom and later expanding it, the recursion-free algorithm records the even-length path from each relevant vertex on a blossom cycle to the base of the blossom.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] When an augmenting path passes through the blossom, the recorded path is used to reconstruct the corresponding path in the original graph, as shown in the figure below.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] This representation preserves the effect of blossom handling while keeping the graph structure static during the search.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] This recursion-free variant exposes a critical opportunity for massive parallelization.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Since the graph is not recursively modified by contraction and lifting, multiple valid vertices in the current search forest can be examined concurrently.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] X-Blossom uses this property to identify multiple vertex-disjoint augmenting paths in a single search iteration, allowing the matching size to increase by more than one per iteration.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] In its implementation, X-Blossom further replaces alternating-tree structures with a path table.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] This table records even-length paths for vertices, regardless of whether they belong to a blossom.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] As a result, the algorithm avoids repeatedly constructing and deconstructing alternating trees and contracted graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] This reduces path-tracing overhead and makes the algorithm more suitable for parallel execution.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Experiments reported in the X-Blossom study showed that its recursion-free design significantly improves the sequential performance, and its parallel version achieves speedups and scalability on multicore platforms across both real-world and synthetic datasets.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] When G is bipartite, there are no odd cycles in G.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] In that case, blossoms will never be found and one can simply remove lines B20 – B24 of the algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The algorithm thus reduces to the standard algorithm to construct maximum cardinality matchings in bipartite graphs where we repeatedly search for an augmenting path by a simple graph traversal: this is for instance the case of the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] The matching problem can be generalized by assigning weights to edges in G and asking for a matching of maximum total weight: this is known as the maximum weight matching problem.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] This problem can be solved by a combinatorial algorithm that uses the unweighted blossom algorithm as a subroutine.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/blossom-algorithm] Efficient, polynomial-time algorithms for this problem are available in several software libraries, including NetworkX, LEDA, and the LEMON graph library.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In the mathematical discipline of graph theory, a **matching** or **independent edge set** in an undirected graph is a set of edges without common vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In other words, a subset of the edges is a matching if each vertex appears in at most one edge of that matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Finding a largest matching in a bipartite graph can be treated as a network flow problem.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Finding a largest matching in a general graph is much more difficult; it can be done using Edmonds' blossom algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Given a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), a **matching** *M* in *G* is a set of pairwise non-adjacent edges, none of which are loops; that is, no two edges share common vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] M is a matching *of* $U\subseteq V$ if every vertex in U is incident with an edge in M .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A vertex is **matched** (or **saturated**) if it is an endpoint of one of the edges in the matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Otherwise the vertex is **unmatched** (or **unsaturated**).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A **maximal matching** is a matching *M* of a graph *G* that is not a subset of any other matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A matching *M* of a graph *G* is maximal if every edge in *G* has a non-empty intersection with at least one edge in *M*.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The following figure shows examples of maximal matchings (red) in three graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A **maximum matching** (also known as maximum-cardinality matching) is a matching that contains the largest possible number of edges.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The **matching number** $\nu (G)$ of a graph G is the size of a maximum matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Every maximum matching is maximal, but not every maximal matching is a maximum matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The following figure shows examples of maximum matchings in the same three graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A **perfect matching** is a matching that matches all vertices of the graph.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] That is, a matching is perfect if every vertex of the graph is incident to an edge of the matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Every perfect matching is maximum and hence maximal.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In some literature, the term **complete matching** is used.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In the above figure, only part (b) shows a perfect matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A perfect matching is also a minimum-size edge cover.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Thus, the size of a maximum matching is no larger than the size of a minimum edge cover: ⁠ $\nu (G)\leq \rho (G)$ ⁠.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A graph can only contain a perfect matching when the graph has an even number of vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A **near-perfect matching** is one in which exactly one vertex is unmatched.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Clearly, a graph can only contain a near-perfect matching when the graph has an odd number of vertices, and near-perfect matchings are maximum matchings.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In the above figure, part (c) shows a near-perfect matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] If every vertex is unmatched by some near-perfect matching, then the graph is called factor-critical.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] An **induced matching** is a matching that is the edge set of an induced subgraph.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Given a matching *M*, an **alternating path** is a path that begins with an unmatched vertex and whose edges belong alternately to the matching and not to the matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] An **augmenting path** is an alternating path that starts from and ends on free (unmatched) vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Berge's lemma states that a matching *M* is maximum if and only if there is no augmenting path with respect to M *.* Using Berge's lemma, we can start from any matching M and repeatedly apply augmenting paths until no more augmenting paths are found.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] This reduces the problem of finding a large matching to finding augmented paths.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In any graph without isolated vertices, the sum of the matching number and the edge covering number equals the number of vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] If there is a perfect matching, then both the matching number and the edge cover number are |*V* | / 2.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem states that, in bipartite graphs, the maximum matching is equal in size to the minimum vertex cover.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Via this result, the minimum vertex cover, maximum independent set, and maximum vertex biclique problems may be solved in polynomial time for bipartite graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Hall's marriage theorem provides a characterization of bipartite graphs which have a perfect matching and Tutte's theorem on perfect matchings provides a characterization for arbitrary graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A spectral characterization of the matching number of a graph is given by Hassani Monfared and Mallik as follows: Let G be a graph on n vertices, and $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}>\ldots >\lambda _{k}>0$ be k distinct nonzero purely imaginary numbers where $2k\leq n$ .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Then the matching number of G is k if and only if (a) there is a real skew-symmetric matrix A with graph G and eigenvalues $\pm \lambda _{1},\pm \lambda _{2},\ldots ,\pm \lambda _{k}$ and $n-2k$ zeros, and (b) all real skew-symmetric matrices with graph G have at most $2k$ nonzero eigenvalues.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Note that the (simple) graph of a real symmetric or skew-symmetric matrix A of order n has n vertices and edges given by the nonozero off-diagonal entries of A .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In particular, this shows that any maximal matching is a 2-approximation of a maximum matching and also a 2-approximation of a minimum maximal matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] This inequality is tight: for example, if *G* is a path with 3 edges and 4 vertices, the size of a minimum maximal matching is 1 and the size of a maximum matching is 2.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A generating function of the number of *k*-edge matchings in a graph is called a matching polynomial.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Let *G* be a graph and *mk* be the number of *k*-edge matchings.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] where *n* is the number of vertices in the graph.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Each type has its uses; for more information see the article on matching polynomials.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A fundamental problem in combinatorial optimization is finding a *maximum matching*.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] This problem has various algorithms for different classes of graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In an *unweighted bipartite graph*, the optimization problem is to find a maximum cardinality matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The problem is solved by the Hopcroft-Karp algorithm in time *O*(√*V**E*) time, and there are more efficient randomized algorithms, approximation algorithms, and algorithms for special classes of graphs such as bipartite planar graphs, as described in the main article.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In a *weighted* *bipartite graph,* the optimization problem is to find a maximum-weight matching; a dual problem is to find a minimum-weight matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] This problem is often called **maximum weighted bipartite matching**, or the **assignment problem**.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The Hungarian algorithm solves the assignment problem and it was one of the beginnings of combinatorial optimization algorithms.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] It uses a modified shortest path search in the augmenting path algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] If the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used for this step, the running time of the Hungarian algorithm becomes $O(V^{2}E)$ , or the edge cost can be shifted with a potential to achieve $O(V^{2}\log {V}+VE)$ running time with the Dijkstra algorithm and Fibonacci heap.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In a *non-bipartite weighted graph*, the problem of **maximum weight matching** can be solved in time $O(V^{2}E)$ using Edmonds' blossom algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A maximal matching can be found with a simple greedy algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A maximum matching is also a maximal matching, and hence it is possible to find a *largest* maximal matching in polynomial time.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] It is also possible to find a maximum matching with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] However, no polynomial-time algorithm is known for finding a **minimum maximal matching**, that is, a maximal matching that contains the *smallest* possible number of edges.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A maximal matching with *k* edges is an edge dominating set with *k* edges.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Conversely, if we are given a minimum edge dominating set with *k* edges, we can construct a maximal matching with *k* edges in polynomial time.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Therefore, the problem of finding a minimum maximal matching is essentially equal to the problem of finding a minimum edge dominating set.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Both of these two optimization problems are known to be NP-hard; the decision versions of these problems are classical examples of NP-complete problems.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Both problems can be approximated within factor 2 in polynomial time: simply find an arbitrary maximal matching *M*.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The number of matchings in a graph is known as the Hosoya index of the graph.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] It is #P-complete to compute this quantity, even for bipartite graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] It is also #P-complete to count perfect matchings, even in bipartite graphs, because computing the permanent of an arbitrary 0–1 matrix (another #P-complete problem) is the same as computing the number of perfect matchings in the bipartite graph having the given matrix as its biadjacency matrix.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] However, there exists a fully polynomial time randomized approximation scheme for counting the number of bipartite matchings.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A remarkable theorem of Kasteleyn states that the number of perfect matchings in a planar graph can be computed exactly in polynomial time via the FKT algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The number of perfect matchings in a complete graph *K**n* (with *n* even) is given by the double factorial (*n* − 1)!!.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The numbers of matchings in complete graphs, without constraining the matchings to be perfect, are given by the telephone numbers.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The number of perfect matchings in a graph is also known as the hafnian of its adjacency matrix.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] One of the basic problems in matching theory is to find in a given graph all edges that may be extended to a maximum matching in the graph (such edges are called maximally matchable edges, or **allowed** edges).
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The problem of developing an online algorithm for matching was first considered by Richard M.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] Karp, Umesh Vazirani, and Vijay Vazirani in 1990.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] In the online setting, nodes on one side of the bipartite graph ("clients") arrive one at a time and must either be immediately matched to the other side of the graph ("servers") or discarded.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] This is a natural generalization of the secretary problem and has applications to online ad auctions.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] A simple greedy algorithm is 1/2-competitive.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] For the unweighted maximization case with a random arrival model, Karp, Vazirani and Vazirani gave a randomized algorithm that attains a competitive ratio of 0.632.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/matching-graph-theory] The problem was also studied in a model where clients may switch servers in order to improve the matching, and the goal is to economize on the number of switches while achieving a maximum matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] The problem is a generalization of the maximum cardinality matching problem because it allows edges to carry arbitrary numerical weights.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] When all edge weights are equal, a maximum-weight matching is equivalent to a maximum cardinality matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] The maximum-weight matching problem is solvable in polynomial time using, for example, the $O(EV^{2})$ blossom algorithm, or Gabow's $O(V^{3})$ algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] This contrasts with the problem of computing the (weighted) maximum independent set of vertices in a graph, which is NP-hard.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] By adjusting the given edge weights, algorithms for the maximum-weight matching problem can also be used to solve the **maximum cardinality** maximum-weight matching problem, where the objective is to find, among all matchings with maximum cardinality, one whose total weight is maximised.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] Similar ideas can also be used to solve the maximum cardinality **minimum** weight matching problem.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] In cases where the edge-weighted graph is bipartite, such problems are also known as the assignment problem.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] The edge weights may be positive, negative, or mixed.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] A commonly occurring variant of the problem involves computing a matching that contains as many edges as possible.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] The total weight of the matching is then used as a secondary measure.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] where C is an appropriate positive constant.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] A maximum-weight matching in $G'$ then corresponds to a maximum cardinality maximum-weight matching in G .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] Again, a maximum-weight matching on $G'$ yields a maximum cardinality minimum weight matching in G .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] In both cases, a constant C is needed to force the algorithm to favor matchings with greater cardinality regardless of the edge weights in G .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] The maximum-weight matching problem is solvable in polynomial time.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] Other algorithms are reviewed by Duan and Pettie.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] Their work also proposes an approximation algorithm for general graphs that runs in linear time for any fixed error bound.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] Efficient implementations are available in several software libraries, including NetworkX, LEDA, and the LEMON graph library.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/maximum-weight-matching] Maximum-weight matchings (and their maximum cardinality variants) arise in a wide range of optimization settings.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] In graph theory, a **perfect matching** in a graph is a matching that covers every vertex of the graph.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] More formally, given a graph G with edges E and vertices V, a perfect matching in G is a subset M of E, such that every vertex in V is adjacent to exactly one edge in M.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] The adjacency matrix of a perfect matching is a symmetric permutation matrix.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] A perfect matching is also called a **1-factor**; see Graph factorization for an explanation of this term.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] Every perfect matching is a maximum-cardinality matching, but the opposite is not true.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] In graph (b) there is a perfect matching (of size 3) since all 6 vertices are matched; in graphs (a) and (c) there is a maximum-cardinality matching (of size 2) which is not perfect, since some vertices are unmatched.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] If there is a perfect matching, then both the matching number and the edge cover number equal |*V*| / 2.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] A perfect matching can only occur when the graph has an even number of vertices.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] This can only occur when the graph has an odd number of vertices, and such a matching must be maximum.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] If, for every vertex in a graph, there is a near-perfect matching that omits only that vertex, the graph is also called factor-critical.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] Hall's marriage theorem provides a characterization of bipartite graphs which have a perfect matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] Tutte's theorem on perfect matchings provides a characterization for arbitrary graphs.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] A perfect matching is a spanning 1-regular subgraph, a.k.a. a 1-factor.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] In general, a spanning *k*-regular subgraph is a *k*-factor.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] A spectral characterization for a graph to have a perfect matching is given by Hassani Monfared and Mallik as follows: Let G be a graph on even n vertices and $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}>\ldots >\lambda _{\frac {n}{2}}>0$ be ${\frac {n}{2}}$ distinct nonzero purely imaginary numbers.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] Then G has a perfect matching if and only if there is a real skew-symmetric matrix A with graph G and eigenvalues $\pm \lambda _{1},\pm \lambda _{2},\ldots ,\pm \lambda _{\frac {n}{2}}$ .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] Note that the (simple) graph of a real symmetric or skew-symmetric matrix A of order n has n vertices and edges given by the nonzero off-diagonal entries of A .
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] Deciding whether a graph admits a perfect matching can be done in polynomial time, using any algorithm for finding a maximum cardinality matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] However, counting the number of perfect matchings, even in bipartite graphs, is #P-complete.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] This is because computing the permanent of an arbitrary 0–1 matrix (another #P-complete problem) is the same as computing the number of perfect matchings in the bipartite graph having the given matrix as its biadjacency matrix.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] A theorem of Pieter Kasteleyn states that the number of perfect matchings in a planar graph can be computed exactly in polynomial time via the FKT algorithm.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] An edge-colored graph can induce a number of (not necessarily proper) vertex colorings equal to the number of perfect matchings, as every vertex is covered exactly once in each matching.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] This property has been investigated in quantum physics and computational complexity theory.
[src:blossom-edmonds-contraction/perfect-matching] The **perfect matching polytope** of a graph is a polytope in **R**|E| in which each corner is an incidence vector of a perfect matching.
